            <p><strong>Factory warranties</strong> come from manufacturers and cover defects in materials or workmanship. <strong>Extended warranties</strong> are third-party contracts that cover mechanical failures from normal wear and tear. Most factory warranties last 3-5 years or 36,000-60,000 miles—extended coverage picks up where they leave off.</p>
          </div>

          <h3>Three Types of Coverage</h3>
          
          <p><strong>Powertrain Coverage</strong> ($1,200-$2,400/year):</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Covers engine, transmission, and drivetrain components</li>
            <li>Most affordable option—protects against the most expensive repairs</li>
            <li>Best for reliable vehicle brands with good track records</li>
          </ul>

          <p><strong>Stated Component Coverage</strong> ($1,800-$3,200/year):</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Lists specific covered components (A/C, electrical, suspension)</li>
            <li>Mid-level protection at moderate costs</li>
            <li>Most popular choice for average consumers</li>
          </ul>

          <p><strong>Exclusionary (Bumper-to-Bumper) Coverage</strong> ($2,800-$4,500/year):</p>
          <ul>
            <li>Covers everything EXCEPT specifically listed exclusions</li>
            <li>Most comprehensive protection available</li>
            <li>Best value for luxury vehicles and unreliable brands</li>
